Project Foundations for Data Science: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Marks: 60

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Initial Hypothesis¶

  • Cuisine type can influence in orders requested.
  • During Weekdays frequency of orders increase.
  • Lower costs are more frequent.
  • Greatest-rated restaurants are preferred.
  • Total delivery time influence the frequency of orders.
  • Total order time (Food preparation time + delivery time) influence the frequency of orders.
  • Cuisine type preferences are different between workdays and weekdays.
  • Customers always have multiple cuisine types preferred.

import matplotlib.patheffects as path_effects
import matplotlib as mpl

from scipy.stats import pearsonr


# Global variable to use in plots.
suptitle_param = dict(color='darkslategray', weight='bold', fontsize='x-large')


def get_df_displot(df):
    """Displot of all numerical variables presented in the passed dataframe.
    df: dataframe with at least one numerical variable.
    """
    df_melt = df.select_dtypes(include=np.number).fillna(0).melt()
    df_melt.value = pd.to_numeric(df_melt.value, errors='coerce')
    
    def central_tendency(x, **kwargs):
        ax = plt.gca()
        mean = x.mean()
        ax.axvline(mean, c='k', ls='--', lw=2.5)
        ax.set_title('{}\nMean: {:,.2f}'.format(ax.get_title(), mean))

    sns.set(font_scale=1.5) 
    g = sns.displot(data=df_melt, 
                    x="value", hue="variable", col="variable", legend=False, common_norm=False, 
                    kind="kde", facet_kws={'sharex': False, 'sharey': False})
    g.map(central_tendency, 'value')
    plt.suptitle('Univariate Analysis - Numerical Features', **suptitle_param)
    plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.85)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    

def get_feature_hist_and_boxplot(feature, bins="auto", figsize=(6, 3)):
    """ Boxplot and histogram combined
    feature: pandas.series
    bins: number of bins (default "auto")
    figsize: size of fig (default (6, 3))
    """
    mean = feature.mean()
    median = np.median(feature)
    min_v = feature.min()
    max_v = feature.max()
    
    sns.set(font_scale=.75) 
    f, (ax_box, ax_hist) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid
        sharex=True,  # The X-axis will be shared among all the subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (.25, .75)},
        figsize=figsize
    )

    # Creating the subplots
    # Boxplot will be created and the mean value of the column will be indicated using some symbol
    sns.boxplot(x=feature, ax=ax_box, color='red',
                showmeans=True, 
                meanprops={"marker":"o", 
                           "markerfacecolor":"goldenrod", 
                           "markeredgecolor":"silver", 
                           "markersize":"10"})
    
    text = ax_box.annotate("Mean {:,.4f}".format(mean), fontsize='small',
                           xy=(mean, -0.15), color='g', weight='bold', ha='center')
    text.set_path_effects([path_effects.Stroke(linewidth=3, 
                                               foreground='black'), path_effects.Normal()])
    ax_box.set_ylabel('BoxPlot\n')
    ax_box.set_xlabel('')
    
    # For histogram
    sns.histplot(x=feature, kde=False, bins=bins, ax=ax_hist)
    ax_hist.axvline(mean, color='g', linestyle='--')      # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist.axvline(median, color='black', linestyle='-') # Add median to the histogram
    
    min_max_pos = 0.05 * ax_hist.get_ylim()[1]
    text = ax_hist.annotate("Median {:,.4f}".format(median), fontsize='small',
                            xy=(median, ax_hist.get_ylim()[1]/2), 
                            color='w', weight='bold', ha='center')
    text.set_path_effects([path_effects.Stroke(linewidth=3, foreground='k'), path_effects.Normal()])
    text = ax_hist.annotate("Min {:,.4f}".format(min_v), fontsize='small',
                            xy=(min_v, min_max_pos), 
                            color='w', weight='bold', ha='left')
    text.set_path_effects([path_effects.Stroke(linewidth=3, foreground='k'), path_effects.Normal()])
    text = ax_hist.annotate("Max {:,.4f}".format(max_v), fontsize='small',
                            xy=(max_v, min_max_pos), 
                            color='w', weight='bold', ha='right')
    text.set_path_effects([path_effects.Stroke(linewidth=3, foreground='k'), path_effects.Normal()])
    
    ax_hist.set_ylabel('HistPlot')
    ax_hist.set_xlabel('')
    
    f.suptitle(feature.name, **suptitle_param)
    plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=1, top=0.9)
    plt.tight_layout()

    plt.show()
    

def get_feature_countplot(feature, rotation=0, top=None, title=None, figsize=(6, 3)):
    """Countplot of a categorical variable
    feature: pandas.series
    rotation: rotation of xticks (default 0)
    top: max rows to return. If none is provided all rows are returned. (Default: None)
    title: title of the plot. If none value is provided, feature names are displayed. 
    (Default: None)
    figsize: size of fig (default (6, 3))
    """
    title = title if title else feature.name
    
    sns.set(font_scale=.75)
    total = len(feature) # Length of the column
    plt.figure(figsize = figsize)
    
    # Convert the column to a categorical data type
    feature = feature.astype('category')
    origin = feature.copy()
    
    labels = feature.value_counts().index
    if top:
        labels = labels[:top]
        feature = feature.loc[feature.isin(labels)]

    ax = sns.countplot(x=feature, palette='Paired', order=labels)
    ax.set_xlabel('')
    
    # custom label calculates percent and add an empty string so 0 value bars don't have a number
    for container in ax.containers:
        labels = [f'{h:.0f}\n( {h/origin.count()*100:0.1f}% )' 
                  if (h := v.get_height()) > 0 else '' for v in container]
        ax.bar_label(container, labels=labels, label_type='edge', 
                     fontsize='small', weight='bold') # color='white', label_type='center'
    ylim = plt.ylim()
    plt.ylim(ylim[0], ylim[1]*1.1)
        
    plt.suptitle(title, **suptitle_param)
    plt.xticks(rotation=rotation)
    plt.tight_layout()
    # plt.autoscale(enable=True, axis='y', tight=False)
    
    plt.show() 
    

def get_unique_values(df):
    """Print how many unique values in regards to the dataset are in each column.
    df: dataframe.
    """
    print('-' * 50)
    for column in df:
        unique = df[column].nunique()
        print(f'{column:<21}: {unique:4d}, repeated: {1.0 - unique/len(df):0.4f}')
        print('-' * 50)
        
        
def get_value_counts(feature, top=None):
    """Print the count of values and percentage of each value in the feature (pandas.series).
    feature: pandas.series.
    top: max rows to return. If none is provided all rows are returned. (Default: None)
    * Return: dataframe.
    """
    return pd.concat([feature.value_counts(), 
                      feature.value_counts(normalize=True)], 
                     axis=1, keys=('Counts', 'Percent')).head(top)


def get_df_boxplot(df, figsize=(10, 3)):
    """Visualize the five-number summary of all numerical variables in dataset: minimum, 
    first quartile (Q1), median (Q2), third quartile (Q3), and maximum.
    df: dataframe.
    size of fig (default (10, 3))
    """
    sns.set(font_scale=.5)
    axes = df.plot(kind='box', subplots=True, sharey=False, fontsize=6, figsize=figsize)
    for ax in axes:
        ax.yaxis.set_major_formatter(mpl.ticker.StrMethodFormatter('{x:,.0f}'))
    plt.suptitle('Numerical variables', **suptitle_param)
    plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=0.75) 
    plt.show()
    
    
def get_feature_barplot(feature, rotation=0, title=None, figsize=(8, 2)):
    """Shows a bar plot of the feature.
    feature: pandas.series.
    rotation: rotation of xticks (default 0).
    title: title of the plot. If none value is provided, feature names are displayed. 
    (Default: None).
    figsize: size of fig (default (8, 2)).
    """
    sns.set(font_scale=0.75)
    ax = feature.plot(kind='bar', figsize=figsize)
    for container in ax.containers:
        ax.bar_label(container, fontsize='small') # color='white', label_type='center'
    ylim = plt.ylim()
    plt.ylim(ylim[0], ylim[1]*1.1)
    title = title if title else feature.name
    plt.suptitle(title, **suptitle_param) 
    plt.xticks(rotation=rotation)
    plt.show()
    
    
def get_df_pointplot(feature_x, feature_y, title=None, figsize=(6,3)):
    """Pointplot of the relation between feature x and feature y.
    feature x: pandas.series.
    feature y: pandas.series.
    title: title of the plot. If none value is provided, feature names are displayed. 
    figsize: size of fig (default (8, 2)).
    """
    title = title if title else f'{feature_x.name} vs {feature_y.name}'
    
    sns.set(font_scale=0.75)
    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    ax = sns.pointplot(x=feature_x, y=feature_y)
    plt.suptitle(title, **suptitle_param)
    plt.show()

# These functions will support transformation required duirng the analysis of the data
from pandas.api.types import is_string_dtype, is_categorical_dtype, is_numeric_dtype

def get_ideal_bins(feature):
    """Return ideal bins for the feature based on the FreedmanDiaconis calculation method
    feature: pandas.series.
    """
    num_data = len(feature)
    irq = np.percentile(feature, 75) - np.percentile(feature, 25)
    bin_width = 2 * irq / np.power(num_data, 1/3)
    num_bins = int((np.max(feature) -  np.min(feature)) / bin_width)  + 1
    return num_bins


def apply_bins(feature, bins=None):
    """Returns a new codified column and the categories associated.
    feature: numerical pandas.series.
    bins: number of categories to codify.
    * return: new codified pandas.series (int), 
              array of the categories associated (string) 
    """
    if not bins:
        bins = get_ideal_bins(feature)
    
    catego = pd.cut(feature, bins=bins)
    codes = catego.cat.codes
    categories = catego.cat.categories.map(lambda x: f'{x.left} - {x.right}')
    return codes, categories


def dataset_encoding(df):
    """Transforming a dataset into numbers to give an overview of the weight that the features 
    could have.
    df: dataframe.
    Returns a new dataframe.
    """
    df_rel = deepcopy(df)
    
    for col in df_rel:
        if is_string_dtype(df_rel[col]):
            df_rel[col] = df_rel[col].astype('category').cat.codes
        elif is_categorical_dtype(df_rel[col]):
            df_rel[col] = df_rel[col].cat.codes
        elif is_numeric_dtype(df_rel[col]):
            df_rel.fillna(0, inplace=True)
            df_rel[col], _ = apply_bins(df_rel[col])
    return df_rel

def get_df_correlation(df):
    """Plot a heatmap of the correlation between numerical variables in df.
    df: dataframe.
    """
    corr = df.corr(numeric_only=True)

    mask = np.zeros_like(corr, dtype=bool)
    mask[np.triu_indices_from(mask)] = True

    sns.set(font_scale=0.75)
    plt.figure(figsize = (5, 3))
    sns.heatmap(corr, annot=True, mask=mask, cmap='vlag')
    plt.title('Correlation between numerical variables', **suptitle_param)
    plt.show()

    
def get_df_pairplot(df):
    """Pairplot of numerical variables in df.
    df: dataframe.
    """
    
    def corrfunc(x, y, **kws):
        (r, p) = pearsonr(x, y)
        ax = plt.gca()
        text = ax.annotate("r={:.2f}, {}".format(r, 'p < 0.001' if p<=0.001 else 'p > 0.001'), 
                           xy=(.1, .9), xycoords=ax.transAxes, color='w', weight='bold')    
        text.set_path_effects([path_effects.Stroke(linewidth=3, foreground='k'), 
                               path_effects.Normal()])
    sns.set(font_scale=0.75) 
    graph = sns.pairplot(data=df.select_dtypes(include=np.number), diag_kind="kde", 
                         corner=True, height=1.75)
    graph.map_lower(corrfunc)
    plt.suptitle('Relation between Numerical Values', **suptitle_param)
    plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.9)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    

def get_heatmap(df, title, cmap='coolwarm'):
    """Heatmap representation of pivot table comparing two variables.
    df: dataframe.
    title: title of the plot.
    """
    sns.set(font_scale=0.75)
    plt.figure(figsize = (8, 2)) # To resize the plot
    sns.heatmap(df,  fmt="d", linewidths=.5, vmin=0)
    plt.suptitle(title, **suptitle_param)
    plt.show()

# These functions have different purposes and will be used during the multivariate analysis
def get_3var_relation_boxplot(df, cat_var, cont_var, hue_var=None, rotation=90, title=None):
    """Boxplot of the cont_var by the cat_var.
    df: dataframe with at least one numerical variable.
    cat_var: name of the categorical variable to plot.
    cont_var: name of the continuous variable to plot.
    hue_var: name of the third variable as classifier to plot.
    rotation: rotation of xticks (default 90).
    title: title of the plot. If none value is provided, feature names are displayed. (Default: None).
    """
    title = title if title else f'"{cont_var}" vs "{cat_var}"'
    boxplot_params = dict(y=df[cont_var], x=df[cat_var])
    if hue_var: 
        boxplot_params['hue'] = df[hue_var]
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))
    sns.set(font_scale=0.75)
    sns.boxplot(**boxplot_params)
    plt.xticks(rotation=rotation)
    plt.title(title, **suptitle_param)
    plt.show()

  • The cost of orders shows a right-skewed distribution with a mean of approx. USD \$ 16.5 per order. The 50% of orders are below USD 14.14.

  • The delivery time has a left-skewed distribution. Half of the orders took less than 25 min to be delivered after the preparation is completed.
  • The total order time seems to have a normalized distribution with a mean and median of approx. 52min.
  • There are 14 different cuisine types in the data collected. American food is the most popular (30.8%) followed by Japanese (24.8%), Italian (15.7%), and Chinese (11.3%). These four cuisine types accumulate 83% of placed orders.

  • In rating, the percentage of not given value is 38.8%, and treated as a category, belongs to the greatest frequency. Other values are 5 (31%), 4 (20.3%), and 3 (9.9%).

# Preparing the data to calculate the total rating counts and average rating
df_promotion = (df.groupby('restaurant_name')
                  .agg({'rating_value': ['mean', 'count'],
                        'order_id': 'count'}))
df_promotion.columns = ['rating_mean', 'rating_count', 'total_orders']

# Calculating how many orders do not provide any rates, in percentage.
df_promotion['percent_missing_rates'] = 1 - (df_promotion.rating_count / df_promotion.total_orders)

# Sorting and filtering the data
df_promotion = df_promotion[(df_promotion.rating_count>50) & (df_promotion.rating_mean>4)]
df_promotion = df_promotion.sort_values(['rating_mean', 'rating_count'], ascending=False)

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]¶

🔴 $\color{red}{\text{Conclusions:}}$¶

I have analyzed a dataset of 1,898 order details related to the food delivery service. The data spanned a group of records across 178 different restaurants and 14 different cuisine types. The main interest here is to understand how the variables can influence the number of orders. From a business perspective, having a better understanding of how data behaves could provide the knowledge to determine the factors that affect the number of orders and thus be able to align the required work capacity.

I have been able to conclude that:

  • 36% of clients have requested the delivery service more than once.
  • There is an increase in the media for the delivery time on weekdays, this could be related to highest-traffic on those days.
  • More orders are placed (71.2%) on weekends than on weekdays.
  • The top 5 restaurants in terms of orders received are: "Shake Shack" (11.5%), "The Meatball Shop" (7%), "Blue Ribbon Sushi" (6%), "Blue Ribbon Fried Chicken" (5%), and "Parm" (4%). In these restaurants, between 17% and 37% of clients have requested food from the same restaurant more than once.
  • The average cost per order is USD \$ 16.5. The 29.2% of orders cost more than 20 dollars.
  • American food is the favority cuisine type on weekdays and on weekends.
  • American, Japanese, Italian, and Chinese cuisine types accumulate 83% of placed orders.
  • French cuisine represents only 0.9% of the preferences, but holds the highest median cost. The highest prices are found in the chinese food (11.3% of the preferences).
  • Korean food takes more time on weekends than on weekdays, meanwhile, Spanish food takes more time on weekdays than on weekends. This could be related a decrease in the number of employees available or an increase in the orders placed.
  • The lowest registered rating has the highest average delivery time.
  • The highest rating has also the highest average cost per order. Highest cost could be related with highest quality.
  • There are only 4 restaurants that have a rating count greater than 50 and an average rating greater than 4: The Meatball Shop (avg. rate: 4.5), Blue Ribbon Fried Chicken (avg. rate: 4.3), Shake Shack (avg. rate: 4.3), and Blue Ribbon Sushi (avr. rate: 4.2). Even though Shake Shack is the most popular restaurant, it is not the one with the highest rating.
  • The total revenue generated by the company across all orders is USD \$ 6,166.30. This total excludes 9 orders that have a cost lower than USD \$ 5.00.

🔴 $\color{red}{\text{Recommendations:}}$¶

  • Providing data related to ratings 1 and 2 could help us to identify areas that need to be improved.
  • Further analysis of the types of cuisine is required to investigate the outliers detected when it is Korean, Mediterranean, and Vietnamese cuisine.
  • There is an increase in the media for the delivery time when is a weekday, this could be related to the highest traffic on weekdays. A register of the order time hour could help to dig a little bit more.
  • Procure data for employees available to get a better understanding of why preparing food time increase on weekdays or weekends over the others for some cuisine types.
  • Get data for placed order time could help to build a model that can predict the workload and the highest period of time where more capacity can be required.
